  pages={745-750},
  abstract={Contrastive learning is a recent hot topic in computer vision (CV), natural language processing (NLP), and even a broad perspective of artificial intelligence, which also has obtained increasing attention for self-supervised graph representation learning. However, most graph contrastive learning methods might sub-optimally integrate node features and topological structures in a complex graph with rich information. To address this issue and improve the richness of node representation learned from graphs, we propose a novel contrastive node representation learning in graph via Mutual Channel Distillation(MCD), which utilizes knowledge distillation and multichannel contrastive learning techniques to improve the quality of node embeddings. Our approach applies mutual channel distillation and multi-channel contrastive learning to help the student model and the teacher model learn from each other, allowing for more diversified and informative node representation to be generated. Experimental results demonstrated that MCD yielded competitive performance over baseline models on multiple node classification and clustering benchmark datasets.},
